  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "The 50% midpoint of a fair value gap, wick, order block body, or other price range. It serves as a precise reaction level where price is expected to respect (only wicks touch, no body closes beyond). A body close beyond CE signals violation and potential invalidation, often used for refined entries and directional bias.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a valid PD array: fair value gap (three-candle imbalance), large wick, order block body, or opening gap on the relevant time frame.",
    "Mark the 50% midpoint between the array's boundaries as the consequent encroachment (CE). For a bearish FVG (SIBI), CE is between the first candle's low and third candle's high; for bullish FVG (BISI), between first candle's high and third candle's low. For wicks, use the wick's range; for order blocks, use the body.",
    "Price respect is confirmed when price touches or enters the array but no candle body closes beyond CE; only wicks should tag CE. A body close beyond CE indicates the array is being violated or disrespected.",
    "A body close beyond CE is an early warning of potential gap invalidation; full invalidation requires a close through the entire FVG.",
    "On higher time frames, mark CE of significant wicks or gaps as points of interest, then drop to lower time frames for refined entries.",
    "With bias-aligned context, look for reversal signals (e.g., displacement, rejection, sweep) at CE before entering in the direction of the prior move.",
    "Compare related assets (e.g., ES vs NQ) by observing whether each asset's price reaches or breaks its CE to gauge relative strength."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "CE provides a precise reaction midpoint within FVGs, wicks, or order blocks for refined entries with tighter stops and improved risk-to-reward. Respect of CE supports continuation entries targeting gap fills or liquidity. A close beyond CE warns of invalidation, often leading to gap inversions or continuation through the level. It also validates reversals, sets directional bias, and compares relative strength between correlated assets.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Confusing CE with complete FVG fill – CE is the 50% midpoint, not the full gap.",
    "Ignoring close price – must use candle body close beyond CE, not just wick touch.",
    "Entering at the first touch of CE without waiting for confirmation (e.g., displacement, reversal pattern).",
    "Placing stops too tight without accounting for price wicking to CE before reversing.",
    "Using the full wick or FVG extreme as the reaction point rather than the 50% midpoint.",
    "Treating a mere wick through CE as full invalidation without a close beyond CE or the entire FVG.",
    "Misidentifying array boundaries (e.g., confusing bullish vs. bearish FVG high/low) leading to incorrectly placed CE.",
    "Continuing to trade in the original direction after CE is broken, ignoring reversal signals.",
    "Failing to compare CE across correlated assets, missing relative strength insights.",
    "Not marking Order Block open and mean threshold correctly, leading to wrong CE location.",
    "Confusing CE with Order Block itself – CE is the specific area above the mean threshold.",
    "Confusing CE with single standard deviation, ignoring its nature as a continuous boundary.",
    "Failing to validate with PD array, resulting in lack of confluence for target zones.",
    "Ignoring higher timeframe structure, relying solely on lower timeframe CE decisions."
  ],
